    "recap_headline": "Central Michigan University Athletics",
    "recap_text": "KENT, Ohio \u2013\nOne of Central Michigan's best pitching performances of the season.\nUnfortunately, Kent State was a bit better.\nThe Golden Flashes took advantage of a Central Michigan error in scoring two unearned runs in the fifth inning on Saturday in handing the Chippewas a 3-2 loss in the game 2 of a three-game Mid-American Conference series at Kent State's Schoonover Stadium.\nThe Chippewas, 7-9, 1-4 MAC, will attempt to avoid the sweep on Sunday when they and the Golden Flashes (14-4, 4-1) play the series finale (1 p.m.).\nTyson Potts\n, a senior transfer from Wayland Baptist, combined with freshman\nCameron Niehaus\nto give CMU one of its best mound performances of the season.\nPotts, making his second start in a CMU uniform, allowed three runs (one earned) on seven hits over five innings. Niehaus tossed three hitless innings, striking out three. The lone blemish on Niehaus' ledger was a hit batter leading off the seventh.\nBryson Webb\ngave CMU the lead with a one-out solo homer in the second inning. It was Webb's second homer in as many days and his third of the season.\nThe Golden Flashes tied it in the third on a bunt base hit, a CMU error, a passed ball and a sacrifice fly.\nKent State went ahead in the fifth when Kolton Schaller was hit by a pitch and took second when Brody Williams was safe on an error. They were bunted into scoring position and then Schaller scored on a single to put Kent State in front, 2-1.\nWilliams then scored from third on a double steal.\nThe Chippewas threatened in the ninth when\nBrady Krzciok\nsingled and scored on a Webb double. Webb moved to third on a flyout, but then Kent State closer Evan Holewinski got a strikeout and a groundout to end it."
  },
